A lot of the appeal of using `{marginaleffects}` is getting predictions and comparisons on the original scale of the data.
However, since this filled-pause data has predicted probabilities ranging from so close to 0 up to the middle of the probability space, it's advisable to carry out the remaining analyses in the logit space, or at least do both and compare the results.

## Getting Treatment Effects

We can estimate the average effect of gender, keeping all other factors the same, by calculating the Average Treatment Effect (ATE).
To do this, we create two copies of the original dataset: one where all `gender` has been set to `woman`, the other where it's all set to `man`.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
to_mod |>
 mutate(
   gender = "woman"
 ) ->
 faux_woman

to_mod |>
 mutate(
   gender = "man"
 ) ->
 faux_man
```
:::


Then, we can get the predicted values for these two counterfactual datasets.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
predictions(
  um_model,
  newdata = faux_woman,
  type = "link"
) ->
 faux_woman_pred

predictions(
  um_model,
  newdata = faux_man,
  type = "link"
) ->
 faux_man_pred
```
:::


Then, if we take the difference between the predictions and average them, we'll get the ATE.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
mean(
  faux_woman_pred$estimate - faux_man_pred$estimate
)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
[1] 1.703695
```


:::
:::


A way to do this more directly is to use `marginaleffects::avg_comparisons()`.


::: {#tbl-gender-comp .cell tbl-cap='Average Treatment Effect for gender'}

```{.r .cell-code}
avg_comparisons(
  um_model,
  variables = "gender",
  type = "link"
) |> 
 tt()
```

