::: {.callout-note collapse="true"}
## Aside

`speaker` is an important grouping variable in the data, and `gender` is a between-group predictor.
When estimating the average treatment effect of a between-group variable, we might want to use a summarized version of the original data.

This code will give is the first row from each speaker for each following segment, with a fixed `relative_rate` of 1.
The `total_rate` predictor is another between-group variable.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
to_mod |>
 slice(
   .by = c(speaker, fol_class),
   1
 ) |>
 mutate(
   relative_rate = 1
 ) -> 
 speaker_grid
```
:::


Now we can get the average treatment effect based on this speaker grid.
I'll further break out the effect by `fol_class`, because not every level of `fol_class` was equally frequent, so collapsing across it in this speaker grid may give us an unrepresentative estimate.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
avg_comparisons(
  um_model,
  variables = "gender",
  by = "fol_class",
  newdata = speaker_grid,
  type = "link"
) |> 
 arrange(desc(estimate)) |> 
 tt()
```

