## Getting expected predictions and slopes

We can get the "expected" predictions from the model by setting up a representative prediction grid.
We'll start with a focus on the language change in progress.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
dob_gender_grid <-  datagrid(
  model = um_model,
  gender = unique,
  dob = 1900:1990,
  total_rate = 5.3,
  relative_rate = 1,
  fol_class = "pause"
)
```
:::


When we use this prediction grid, we'll want to set `re_formula = NA`.
This is a brms specific argument that sets the random effects to 0 when getting our predictions.
We want to do this because the `speaker` variable is set to the value of the speaker with the most data.
They're not necessarily a representative speaker, so we don't want to include the random intercepts and slopes when estimating the predictions.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
um_model |>
 predictions(
   newdata = dob_gender_grid,
   re_formula = NA
 ) ->
 dob_gender_pred
```
:::



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code  code-fold="true" code-summary="Plotting code"}
dob_gender_pred |>
 ggplot(
   aes(dob, estimate, color = gender)
 ) +
 geom_lineribbon(
   aes(ymin = conf.low, ymax = conf.high),
   alpha = 0.8
 ) +
 ylim(0,1) +
 theme_sub_legend(
   position = "inside",
   position.inside = c(0.2, 0.5)
 )
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![Estimated "um" probability by date of birth and gender](index_files/figure-typst/fig-change-1.svg){#fig-change}
:::
:::


One of the questions we had was whether the rate of change was the same for men and women.
We can get estimated slopes over year of birth with the `slopes()` and `avg_slopes()` functions.
This next table is telling us what the average effect of 1 year of dob is on the log-odds of "um".


::: {#tbl-slope1 .cell tbl-cap='Average expected slope over date of birth'}

```{.r .cell-code}
avg_slopes(
  um_model,
  variables = "dob",
  newdata = dob_gender_grid,
  type = "link",
  re_formula = NA
) |>
 tt()
```

