The interaction effect doesn't seem that reliable.
:::

Now, let's turn to speech rate effects.
At a first pass, we'll get just the predicted log-odds of "um" over relative speech rate.
For this, I'll set up a relatively balanced prediction grid across all predictors.
I'm making the spread of values across the numeric predictors a little less dense to speed up computation.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
rate_grid <- datagrid(
    model = um_model,
    relative_rate = seq(1/3, 3/1, length = 10),
    total_rate = n_quantiles(10),
    gender = unique,
    fol_class = unique,
    dob = seq(1900, 1990, length = 10)
  )
```
:::


Now, I'll get the average predicted "um" probability across `relative_rate`.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
avg_predictions(
  um_model,
  newdata = rate_grid,
  by = c("relative_rate"),
  re_formula = NA
) -> 
rate_pred
```
:::



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code  code-fold="true" code-summary="Plotting code"}
rate_pred |> 
 ggplot(
   aes(relative_rate, estimate)
 ) + 
 geom_lineribbon(
   aes(ymin = conf.low, ymax = conf.high)
 ) +
 scale_x_log10() +
 ylim(0,1)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![Expected 'um' probability by `relative_rate`, 
marginalizing over all other predictors
](index_files/figure-typst/fig-rate-pred-1.svg){#fig-rate-pred}
:::
:::


We can break down the these predictions by another hesitation indicator: the following segment


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
avg_predictions(
  um_model,
  newdata = rate_grid,
  by = c("relative_rate", "fol_class"),
  re_formula = NA
) -> 
 rate_by_fol
```
:::



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code  code-fold="true" code-summary="Plotting code"}
rate_by_fol |>
 ggplot(
   aes(relative_rate, estimate, color = fol_class)
 ) +
 geom_lineribbon(
   aes(ymin = conf.low, ymax = conf.high),
   alpha = 0.6
 ) +
 geom_line(
   linewidth = 1.5
 ) +
 ylim(0, 1) +
 scale_x_log10() +
 theme_sub_legend(
   position = "inside",
   position.inside = c(0.85, 0.5)
 )
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![Expected 'um' probability by `relative_rate`, 
and `fol_class`,
marginalizing over all other predictors
](index_files/figure-typst/fig-rate-fol-pred-1.svg){#fig-rate-fol-pred}
:::
:::


One of the questions I'd asked above is whether the effect of relative speech rate is affected by how baseline fast or slow a speaker is.
We can explore that here with `avg_slopes()`.
Because `relative_rate` is a ratio, I'll set `slope = "dyex"`.
This means the estimated slopes will describe how the log-odds of "um" changes as `relative_rate` increases by 100% (instead of +1).


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
avg_slopes(
  um_model,
  newdata = rate_grid,
  variables = "relative_rate",
  by = "total_rate",
  slope = "dyex",
  type = "link",
  re_formula = NA
) ->
 rate_by_total_slope
```
:::



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code  code-fold="true" code-summary="Plotting code."}
rate_by_total_slope |>
 ggplot(
   aes(total_rate, estimate)
 ) + 
 geom_lineribbon(
   aes(
     ymin = conf.low,
     ymax = conf.high
   )
 ) +
 scale_x_log10() +
 labs(
   y = "relative rate slope"
 )
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![Estimated slope of `relative_rate` by `total_rate`
](index_files/figure-typst/fig-rate-total-1.svg){#fig-rate-total}
:::
:::


It doesn't seem like someone being an overall slower or faster talker interacts with the effect of relative speech rate.

Another thing to ask is whether the effect of relative speech rate has been affected by the language change!
To look at this, we'll get the average slope of `relative_rate`, grouped by date of birth and gender.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
avg_slopes(
  um_model,
  newdata = rate_grid,
  variables = "relative_rate",
  by = c("dob", "gender"),
  slope = "dyex",
  type = "link",
  re_formula = NA
) ->
 rate_by_change_slope
```
:::



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code  code-fold="true" code-summary="Plotting code."}
rate_by_change_slope |>
 ggplot(
   aes(dob, estimate, color = gender)
 ) + 
 geom_hline(
   yintercept = 0
 ) +
 geom_lineribbon(
   aes(ymin = conf.low, ymax = conf.high),
   alpha = 0.6
 ) +
 geom_line(
   linewidth = 1.5
 ) +
 theme_sub_legend(
   position = "inside", 
   position.inside = c(0.5, 0.9),
   direction = "horizontal"
 )
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![Estimated slope of `relative_rate` by `dob` and `gender`
](index_files/figure-typst/fig-rate-change-1.svg){#fig-rate-change}
:::
:::


The result is a bit unexpected: It looks like the effect of relative speech rate has been growing stronger for women, and was never all that reliable for men.

# More kinds of models

As I said above, while I used `{brms}` to fit the model for this tutorial, the functions covered here would work in just the same way for many other kinds of models.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
flat_um_model <- glm(
  um ~ I(dob-1943) * gender * fol_class *
   I(log(total_rate/5.3)) *
   I(log(relative_rate)),
  data = to_mod,
  family = binomial
)
```
:::



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
flat_um_model |>
 predictions(
   newdata = datagrid(
     dob = 1900:1990,
     gender = unique,
     fol_class = "pause",
     relative_rate = 1
   )
 ) |>
 ggplot(
   aes(dob, estimate, color = gender)
 ) + 
   geom_lineribbon(
     aes(ymin = conf.low, ymax = conf.high),
     alpha = 0.8
   )+
   ylim(0,1)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-typst/unnamed-chunk-35-1.svg)
:::
:::


They also work well for non-linear smooths.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
non_linear <- brm(
  um ~ gender + s(I(dob-1943), by = gender) + (1|speaker),
  data = to_mod,
  family = bernoulli(),
  backend = "cmdstanr",
  cores = 4,
  file = "models/non_linear"
)
```
:::



::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
non_linear |>
 predictions(
   newdata = datagrid(
     dob = 1900:1990,
     gender = unique
   ),
   re_formula = NA
 ) |>
 ggplot(
   aes(dob, estimate, color = gender)
 ) + 
   geom_lineribbon(
     aes(ymin = conf.low, ymax = conf.high),
     alpha = 0.8
   )+
   ylim(0,1)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-typst/unnamed-chunk-37-1.svg)
:::
:::


We can even get a difference curve


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
non_linear |>
 slopes(
   newdata = datagrid(
     dob = 1900:1990,
     gender = unique
   ),
   variables = "gender",
   by = "dob",
   type = "link",
   re_formula = NA
 ) |>
 ggplot(
   aes(dob, estimate)
 ) +
   geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linewidth = 0.5)+
   geom_lineribbon(
     aes(ymin = conf.low, ymax = conf.high),
     alpha = 0.8
   )
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-typst/unnamed-chunk-38-1.svg)
:::
